Figure 1. Fraction (%) of the FGL, FGG and FGA among ccRCC case subgroups. P-values between subgroups were as follows: males vs females (P=0.002), age (<50, vs 50 years, P=0.06), any family history of cancer (P=0.02), stage (P<0.00001), grade (P<0.0001), ever vs never smoking (P=0.05), VHL wild-type cases vs those with VHL promoter hypermethylation (P=0.03), VHL wild-type cases vs those with VHL sequence alterations (P=0.17). REF, referent group.

cBioPortalFraction Genome AlteredgainlostcBioPortalfraction of genome gained (FGG) fraction of the genome lost (FGL)TCGACNVFGAFGGFGL The Fraction Genome Altered provided by cBioPortal is overall and does not distinguish between gain and lost. the algorithm of cBioPortal was intended to calculate fraction of genome gained (FGG) and fraction of the genome lost (FGL) respectively, and clinical information was used to compare the differences among the groups. Input the CNV data of TCGA, calculate FGA, FGG, and FGL, and reproduce the figures of the article.

Application Scenarios

cBioPortalFraction Genome Altered (FGA) Our own sequencing data were used to calculate Fraction Genome Altered (FGA) using the algorithm of cBioPortal.

TCGAFGAFGGFGL Alternatively, the data from TCGA can be used to calculate the FGA, FGG and FGL of different clinical groups and conduct difference tests.

meansep Custom functions calculate mean, se and p values

cal_ms <- function(x,y){
  table1=data.frame()
  for (i in y) {
    name=summarySE(x,measurevar=c(colnames(x)[ncol(x)]), groupvars=c(colnames(x)[i]))[[1]]
    mean=summarySE(x, measurevar=c(colnames(x)[ncol(x)]), groupvars=c(colnames(x)[i]))[[3]] #mean
    se=summarySE(x, measurevar=c(colnames(x)[ncol(x)]), groupvars=c(colnames(x)[i]))[[5]] #se
    
    table=data.frame(group=rep(colnames(x)[i],length(mean)),subgroup=name,mean=mean,se=se)
    table1=rbind(table1,table)
    
  }
  table1$subgroup=factor(table1$subgroup,levels=unique(table1$subgroup))
  table1$group=factor(table1$group,levels=unique(table1$group))
  return(table1)
}#meanse,  # Calculate mean and se, sort
cal_p=function(x,y){
  table2=data.frame()
  for (i in y) {
    m<-aov(x[,ncol(x)]~as.factor(x[,i]))
    summary(m)
    table=cbind(rep(colnames(x)[i],nrow((TukeyHSD(m))[[1]])),(TukeyHSD(m))[[1]])
    table2=rbind(table2,table) 
  }
  return(table2)
}#p  # Calculate the p value
signif=function(table1,table2){
  signif1=c()
  for (i in 1:length(table(table2[,1]))) {
    signif1=c(signif1,"Ref",table2[table2[,1]==levels(table1[,1])[i],5][1:length(table1[table1[,1]==names(table(table2[,1])[i]),"subgroup"])-1])
  }#p  # Extract the P-value
  for (i in 1:length(signif1)) {
    if (!is.na(as.numeric(signif1[i]))) {
      signif1[i]=ifelse(signif1[i]>0.05,"",ifelse(signif1[i]<=0.0001,"****",ifelse(signif1[i]<=0.001,"***",ifelse(signif1[i]<=0.01,"**",ifelse(signif1[i]<=0.05,'*')))))
    }
  }#  # Conversion Markup
  return(signif1)
}#  # Prepare the data for salient marking
mar=function(tableGL){
  mar=round(max(tableGL[,"mean"]+tableGL[,"se"]),1)+0.05
  return(mar)
}#ggplot  #ggplot coordinate length

FGAFGGFGL

Calculate FGA, FGG and FGL

data=data.frame()

for (i in 1:length(table(Segment$sample))) {
  tmp=Segment[Segment$sample==names(table(Segment$sample))[i],]
  if (length(tmp[abs(tmp$value)>0.2,"bases"][6])==0) {
    FGA=0
  } else {
    FGA=sum(tmp[abs(tmp$value)>0.2,"bases"])/sum(tmp[,"bases"])
  }
  
  if (length(tmp[tmp$value>0.2,"bases"][6])==0) {
    FGG=0
  } else {
    FGG=sum(tmp[tmp$value>0.2,"bases"])/sum(tmp[,"bases"])
  }
  
  if (length(tmp[tmp$value<(-0.2),"bases"][6])==0) {
    FGL=0
  } else {
    FGL=sum(tmp[tmp$value<(-0.2),"bases"])/sum(tmp[,"bases"])
  }
  
  tmp=data.frame(Patient=names(table(Segment$sample))[i],FGA=FGA,FGG=FGG,FGL=FGL)
  data=rbind(data,tmp)
}

Figure

Reproduce the Figure of the literature

meansepAONVATukeyHSDreference Calculate the mean, se and p values and draw graphs. The test method used here is AONVA, and TukeyHSD is used for inter-group comparison (the results only take the significance of the reference group and other groups for easy display).

table1=cal_ms(All[,c(1:6,7)],2:6) #() #(Keep the last column as the target variable)
table2=cal_p(All[,c(1:6,7)],2:6)#() #(Keep the last column as the target variable)
signif1=signif(table1,table2)
table3=cal_ms(All[,c(1:6,9)],2:6) #FGL
table4=cal_p(All[,c(1:6,9)],2:6)  #FGL

table5=cal_ms(All[,c(1:6,8)],2:6) #FGG
table6=cal_p(All[,c(1:6,8)],2:6)  #FGG

Precautions

FGAcnvCNV callingsegmentation fileCNV callingcnvegmentation fileStartEndNum_ProbesSegment_MeanFGAcbioportal The calculation of FGA relies on cnv data, namely the segmentation file generated by CNV calling. So different CNV calling processes and different parameter Settings will generate different cnv data (specifically, you can refer to Start, End, Num_Probes, Segment_Mean in the egmentation file). This is also the reason why the FGA of some patients in the above calculation results differs from that of cbioportal.

TCGAcnvxenaTCGAGDCGDCSNP_N_GenomeWideSNP_6_D01_680066.nocnv_grch38.seg.v2.txtcbioportalC11b Besides, If you want to calculate the cnv data from TCGA by yourself, please note that only TCGA on xena (not GDC) and SNP_N_GenomeWideSNP_6_D01_680066.nocnv_grch38.seg.v2.txt on the GDC official website can be used with cbiopor Consistency on tal (differences in the C11b version).

GDCsegmentation fileSegment_Meanlog2R:https://docs.gdc.cancer.gov/Data/Bioinformatics_Pipelines/CNV_Pipeline/ Download segmentation from the GDC official website The log2R Segment_Mean and formula in the file (website: < https://docs.gdc.cancer.gov/Data/Bioinformatics_Pipelines/CNV_Pipeline/ >).

copy number If it is your own sequencing data, you should pay attention. If it is a copy number, it also needs to be converted according to the above formula.
